{"id":"2211.12369","submitter":"Liping Li","authors":"Liping Li","title":"Ray-Knight compactification of birth and death processes","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A birth and death process is a continuous time Markov chain with the minimal\nstate space $\\mathbb{N}$, whose transition matrix is standard and whose density\nmatrix is the given birth-death matrix. Birth and death processes are unique if\nand only if $\\infty$ is entrance or natural. When $\\infty$ is neither entrance\nnor natural, there have appeared two methods in history to obtain all birth and\ndeath processes. The first one is an analytic treatment put forward by Feller\nin 1959, and the second is a probabilistic construction completed by Wang in\n1958.\n  In this paper we will raise a third way by virtue of the Ray-Knight\ncompactification. This new way has benefits of both analytic and probabilistic\ntreatments. By Ray-Knight compactification, every birth and death process\nadmits a modification regarded as a Ray process on\n$\\mathbb{N}_\\infty=\\mathbb{N}\\cup \\{\\infty\\}$. All of them are further\nclassified into two classes: One is the class of celebrated Doob processes and\nthe other one is the class of Feller $Q$-processes. Every birth and death\nprocess in the second class is actually a Feller process on\n$\\mathbb{N}_\\infty$. We will derive the expression of its infinitesimal\noperator, which indicates probabilistic heuristics for its boundary behaviours\nat $\\infty$. Furthermore, utilizing transformations of killing and\nIkeda-Nagasawa-Watanabe's piecing out, we will also give a probabilistic\nconstruction for all birth and death processes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Nov 2022 16:04:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-23"}
